\f1\b Replication code synthetic weights.R
\f2\b0 \
R file.\
The script uses the replication data and estimates optimal synthetic weights.\
For each \'93treated\'94 municipality, the code finds the optimal weights such that the synthetic control municipality has pre-treatment trends in homicides that are maximally similar to those of the treated municipality.\
The output of this script is a Stata database containing vectors of numeric identifiers (idunico) and optimal weights.\
\

\f1\b Replication Do File.do
\f2\b0 \
Stata file.\
The do file uses the replication data and reproduces all the tables, graphs, and results presented in the paper.\
\
\

\f1\b To replicate the results presented in the paper:
\f2\b0 \
\
1. Use the replication code in R to estimate optimal synthetic weights for each treated municipality. \
\
Eight different sets of synthetic weights have to be estimated according to\
	1. Type of treatment: captures of leaders vs. captures of lieutenants.\
	2. Geographic location: treated municipalities (direct) vs. neighboring municipalities (neigh).\
	3. Variable of interest : homicides of males between 15 and 39 yo (dto) vs. homicides among the rest of the population (rest)\
\
Given computational and time constraints, we estimated each vector of weights separately. \
The code indicates the lines that have to be changed to specify the new parameters in each iteration.\
\
2. Merge the resulting vector of weights with the replication dataset.\
The replication dataset already contains the eight vectors of optimal weights.\
\
3. Run the replication do file in Stata. The code contains the commands for each model.\
